where x j is the j-th component of the vector for fault slip, ai is the superposition coeÔ¨Écient of the i-th
basis function, and œÜij is the j-th component of the vector for the i-th basis function. Here we introduce
unit fault slip, which uses a bicubic B-spline deÔ¨Åned on n grid points distributed on the fault plane as the
basis functions [16]. Crustal deformation during an earthquake is considered linear elastic deformation.
Therefore, if we can compute the Green‚Äôs functions gki , which describe the displacement response in
the k-th observation point on the ground surface due to a unit fault slip œÜij , we can describe the fault slip
using a linear equation where the unknowns are ai as follows:
Ga = d,

(2)

where G is an m √ó n matrix, the components of which are g ji ; a is n-dimensional vector, the components
of which are ai ; and d is an m-dimensional vector, the components of which are d j , which is the observed
displacement in the j-th observation point. m > n in many cases, but because G is usually an illconditioned or sometimes a singular matrix, we regularized G using prior knowledge of the smoothness
of a [12]. Assuming that a is deÔ¨Åned using predeÔ¨Åned grid points, we can describe the condition as
ak‚àí1,l + ak+1,l + ak,l‚àí1 + ak,l+1 ‚àí 4ak,l = 0.

(3)

Here the subscripts are arranged so that ak,l describes the displacement of the grid point (k, l). If this
constraint is rewritten in matrix notation, we Ô¨Ånd that La = 0, with an n √ó n matrix L, and the target
equation can be written as
