Application example

We applied the method to compute several hundred crustal deformation analyses of an inversion of fault
slip of the 2011 Tohoku-oki Earthquake. The results by an HFM and a model with a simpliÔ¨Åed geometry
and material properties were compared.
The target region was 0 ‚â§ x ‚â§ 784 km west-to-east, 0 ‚â§ y ‚â§ 976 km south-to-north, and ‚àí400 ‚â§
z ‚â§ 0 km vertically, as shown in Figure 5. The crustal structure consisted of four layers, and the material
properties were deÔ¨Åned based on the data in [13] (see Table 1). We constructed two FE models using the
parameters with which the numerical solution converged to the analytical solution in [5]. The HFM was
constructed with a 1 km resolution, which is the same as that reported in [8]. The simpliÔ¨Åed model (SM)
was constructed without considering the geometry or material heterogeneity, which corresponds to the
analytical solution in the homogeneous half-space (see Figure 7). The height of the ground surface in the
SM was the average of HFM. The HFM had 127,263,300 DOFs, and contained 37,255,182 tetrahedral
elements and 35,585,620 voxel elements. GPS displacement data from the GNSS Earth Observation
Network System (GEONET) [2] was used for the crustal deformation data, and the seaÔ¨Çoor data were
taken from [6], [7], and [14] (see Figure 5). The grid points used to input the Green‚Äôs functions were
located at 30 km intervals in the range 310 ‚â§ x ‚â§ 670km and 200 ‚â§ y ‚â§ 710km. Unit fault slips
were applied at points satisfying two conditions: points in the area where the PaciÔ¨Åc Plate and the upper
mantle or crust were in direct contact, and points located in the west of the Japan Trench. The number
of the points which satisfy the conditions was 137 (see Figure 6). Since we had to compute Green‚Äôs
functions in x and y direction on the fault plane, the total number of Green‚Äôs functions to compute was
137 √ó 2 = 274.
We calculated the fault slip in the 2011 Tohoku-oki Earthquake using the HFM and SM. First, we
estimated the fault slip using the L-curve method; however, we found many high-frequency components
of the fault slip distribution in both of the results. Then we changed the parameter for regularization
to a larger one so that the estimation results followed a smoother distribution. Then the results were
obtained without the inÔ¨Çuence of the high-frequency components, as shown in Figure 8. The absolute
diÔ¨Äerences were larger nearer the trench axis, which may be due to diÔ¨Äerences in the geometry between
the two models. From these results, we can see the inÔ¨Çuence of model simpliÔ¨Åcation on the fault slip
estimation results. Therefore, the HFM should be used to model fault slip, and the method to compute
the Green‚Äôs functions based on capacity computing was eÔ¨Äective for this task. However, the estimated
results obtained using the L-curve method included high-frequency components, which may be because
the uncertainty in the Green‚Äôs function was neglected. To take this uncertainty into account, both the
solver and capacity computation method should be modiÔ¨Åed so that a Monte Carlo approach can be
applied to the crust deformation analysis.
We computed 274 Green‚Äôs functions as described in section 2.4 using 16 computation nodes, each of
which had two 6-core Intel(R)Xeon X5680 processors running at 3.33 GHz, and 48 GB of DDR3-1333
memory. The timing between jobs was tg = 8 min, which was based on the input time for mesh data.
The total time for computation was 21.4 h. Suppose that the computation of every Green‚Äôs function
takes 4084 s when it is singly executed, the ideal computation time for 274 Green‚Äôs functions is 4084 s
√ó 274 / 16 nodes 19.4 h. Since a computation node has to wait 15 tg = 2 h at maximum to start the
computation, 21.4 h is almost identical to the ideal computation time and parallel eÔ¨Éciency does not
suÔ¨Äer much with our capacity computing method. The maximum memory usage within a computation
node was 40 GB.
